multICard case is an IC card case which user can choose how to hold it.

Assemble it by looking at the 3D data(you need glues), and you are finished!

title: Anet A8 rear extension for larger heatbed

description.text:
ANET A8 - EXTENDED VERSION 220x275mm!

There is an easy and inexpensive way to increase the build space on your Anet A8 by
55mm. It is possible to directly install a larger 220x275mm Hictop heatbed on the A8 printer, the screw locations are identical, so the bed will fit directly on the stock heatbed carrier, but to utilize its larger dimensions, the rear plate must be moved backwards by 25mm so longer y-bearing rods (450mm) as well as longer M8 rods can be installed, which are both necessary to get those required 55mm of extra y-motion. Moving the rear plate can now be easily done with this adapter I created.

Another pleasant side effect which I have noticed with this conversion is that the adapters also seem to to reduce vibrations during printing.

Print this adapter part, one unchanged and another one mirrored for the opposite side. Remove the rear plate on the A8 and mount the printed adapter parts in its place using the same screws and nuts that your rear plate was mounted with. You can tighten the screws through the openings in the adapter part. Then attach your rear plate to the adapter with an M5 screw and nut in the middle. Use a large washer. After tightening the adapter to the chassis, you can now use the two original screw holes for M5 screws and nuts to secure the rear plate even better, but first you´ll have to enlarge the openings on the rear plate to 5mm, be careful when drilling! Once everything else is tightened, you can add another M5 screw and nut to crosswise secure the adapter to the chassis, but it will also work without it. If you do so, then start drilling by making a smaller hole first before using a full 5mm drill bit.

Remember to be careful and go really slowly when drilling any of your printers acrylic parts, they will crack very easily if pushed too hard!

Replace your y bearing rods with 450mm long ones and also install longer M8 rods. Instead of buying new M8 rods, you can also use two M8x50mm bolts and M8x35mm coupling nuts to extend your existing M8 rods.

The adapter has openings which allow it to be bolted to a baseplate if you are using one.

Parts needed:

  • Hictop 275 x 220mm heatbed (12V version)
  • 2 pcs 450x8mm smooth linear bearing rods: http://s.click.aliexpress.com/e/VRBEiQZ
  • longer M8 threaded rods (or alternatively two M8x50mm bolts and two M8x35mm coupling nuts to extend your existing M8 rods)
  • a longer y-belt
  • M5 screws and nuts
  • 2 large M5 washers

Total conversion cost about 40$, build time 2-3 hrs (not including print time).

IMPORTANT NOTE: THE HICTOP HEATBED USES A DIFFERENT PINOUT THAN ANET SO MAKE SURE YOU HAVE CONNECTED IT CORRECTLY BEFORE YOU SWITCH ON YOUR PRINTER!

PLEASE SHARE YOUR MAKE IF YOU PRINT THIS ITEM.

CREATING AND FINALIZING THIS ITEM HAS TAKEN HOURS OF DESIGNING, MODIFICATIONS AND SEVERAL TEST PRINTS TO GET EVERYTHING RIGHT. PLEASE CONSIDER LEAVING A TIP VIA THINGIVERSE IF YOU FIND THIS ITEM USEFUL: http://bit.ly/2szoAhU

Update 1.8.2017:
Leo_N was kind enough to design a modified version of his rear frame brace (visible in the last photo above), which will fit this extended version of the frame. The file for the frame brace has now been added.

remixed_from.title: Z-Axis Induction Sensor & Fan Bracket for MK7 type extruders (Folger Tech)

title: Z-Axis Induction Sensor for Wanhao i3 / MakerSelect 3D - 12mm Z Probe

description.text:
I sliced up and modified TheLost's design to fit the Wanhao Duplicator i3 design. To install you remove the extruder fan and the spacers between that and the heat sink. Use this part in place of the spacers and reassemble. There are other tutorials out there on how to update your Melzi firmware to support auto-leveling, all of which come with drawbacks due to memory constraints. I recommend this modification if you are considering a Ramps 1.4 upgrade.

I left the 3mf file here so you can edit as well. The cylinders used for holes are not subtracted yet so you have the option of the original 3mm or to make the holes 3.2mm or some other size as needed.

NOTE: If you are still using the stock blower then the first version I created will likely not fit. Try the "Stock blower" version which moves the z-probe 3mm further out. It's still a rather tight fit but it should be okay.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15 or 0.2 should be fine

Infill:

75% or more; you don't want this thing bending or snapping if you accidentally ram the build plate!

Notes:

Given the need for rigidity and heat tolerance, ABS is the best bet. PETG is a good second choice but its flexibility might be problematic in this application. PLA is not recommended. My first print was stable with 50% infill but I misconfigured my level settings and ran the hot-end into the build plate, which snapped the mount. I recommend 75% or more infill if you want this to be rigid.

Depending on your print you might have to drill out the 3mm holes. If you have trouble getting the heatsink to fit well then use a drill and expand the holes a little more in the print. I used a 1/8 bit and had to make things a little looser in there before the fit was just right.

The 12mm hole is likely going to be a tight fit and might require a little sanding or filing to get the part to go through. I left it like this because your slicer settings are probably better than mine and you might not have this problem. ;)

You're going to laugh at me...

I actually just used the 3D printer app that comes with Windows 10. I split the model up into parts and resized them according to the dimensions that better suit the Wanhao design. I then added a few cubes and resized them and rotated to add a more solid connection between the probe mount and the fan bracket parts. Finally, I split the excess off the extra parts and made the holes a little wider to accommodate how my slicer tends to make holes a little too snug sometimes; the holes are about 3.2mm wide in this design whereas the screws are 3mm. The z-probe hole is 12mm and is a very snug fit but that is big enough for sandpaper or a nail file to adjust so I didn't bother changing that part.

title: FLSun i3 X-axis carriage with integrated belt tensioner

description.text:
X-axis carriage for the FLSun prusa i3. Remixed the original FLSun model adding an integrated tensioner while trying not to add too much weight.

Extended version moves the hotend mounting point 5mm forward and clearanced so the v6 heater block can be oriented with the long cartridge clamp end towards the rear, allowing better visibility of the nozzle. Y-endstop needs to be adjusted 5mm forward to match.

The factory model has bearing holes 15.3mm in diameter to account for part shrinkage. These were a tight fit on the original part, making it hard to remove the bearings, and on my well-tuned printer they were too accurate, and so too large, leaving the bearings loose. The slotted version solves both of those issues; the bearing holes are modeled at 15.1mm which should give a tight fit with a bit of flexibility. It also helps speed up printing and gives a cleaner, more accurate bearing hole since it is now part of the exterior perimeter, and so can be printed in the same extrusion and without it's own seam.

Note: if using igus or other drylin-style bushings without the metal sleeve stick to the un-slotted version; these bearings need a tight press-fit so that they are squeezed a little in order to achieve tight tolerances on the rods.

Use the test tubes if You want a quick test print to check the dimensional accuracy of your printer at the different IDs, also see more on tuning your printer here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2276869

Printer:

FLSun i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

25%

Notes:

I read that Prusa uses three perimeters with 25% infill on their factory parts, that should be a good balance of strong and light for the carriage. It's also suggested to print the carriage in ABS or PET due to the higher heat resistance.

I suggest printing the tensioner block with 100% infill for best strength and exterior dimensional consistency.

description.text: I wanted a new Iphone holder for my 4runner and it had to have the ability to contain the charger. So I remixed this simple design. I split it into parts as I typically do not like to print with support. Now the real question is if my wife wants one for her car.

Print both parts in ABS. PLA will become too soft or melt in your car.   
I found a use for the scrap i cut off of the 3mm filament after I remove it from the extruder. It makes a perfect pin. The abs crushes in place with a bit of pressure from a pair of needle nose pliers.   
I included a cut in the base for the wire, but as you can see from the pictures, my cable has suffered from years of abuse and is wrapped in electrical tape.   
The plug slot may be a half of a mm too big. Wrap it in tape once to produce a tight grip.   
This fits very firmly in the 2nd slot of my 4runner vent.

comments.text: I am quickly learning just how important feedback is. If you encounter issues with the design, please comment.
comments.author: eae01751

comments.text:
This design is going to be modified. I am going to make it into 3 printable parts. What I have found is that the stock Apple charger works just fine, obviously it does not work for the Lightning charger. However, there are adapters you can print like http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:31429http://www.thingiverse.com/thi.... The other issue I have found is that what works just fine in my 4 runner does not work in my wife's car. Her vents have a much smaller opening. So I will also be redesigning different or customizable clips for the vents.
I also want to be able to print the middle riser horizontally to add strength.
comments.author: eae01751

comments.text: I also included a pic of the failed prints. This is what lead me to including a rib along the back of the holder. I found that at 50% infill, the piece was long enough to break easily with a bit of pressure.

description.text:
A mechanical TrotBot walker.
Video on youtube - https://youtu.be/XorL3H8H0_k

Original walking mechanism based on Ben & Wade Vagle's TrotBot.
See https://www.diywalkers.com for more information on this, and other types of walking machines. They also have a supersized version!

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

Varies

Notes:

Most parts printed at circa 30% infil. Some supports required at ends of arms.
All printed in PLA.
Crankshaft parts are printed at about 80% infill to give strength. Also the crankshaft pieces need to be printed in the correct orientation to maximise against torsion.

Assembly

Quite a bit of assembly required. Some cleaning of parts to ensure that they move smoothly.
In these types of walkers friction is your enemy, make sure parts move easily.

Software used

Orginal linkage design was from www.diywalkers.com.
After printing a sample leg and mounting it on a dummy frame I made some tweaks to the lengths.

  • Linkage simulator - www.linkagesimulator.com - modelling walking gait. File attached
  • Autodesk Fusion360 - design and assembly testing. It also generates the CNC mill tool path.
  • Simplified 3D - slicer for 3d printer
  • Octoprint - 3d Print server software
Parts

Main Assembly

  • Motors, gears, belts and beams are from MakeBlock
  • Plywood chassis panels are CNC cut using a Carvey from Inventables
  • 3d printed legs, crankshaft and brackets are printed using a Rob3d printer

Control system:
It is controlled via bluetooth from any phone. It uses Adafruit Bluefruit LE Connect app. The arduino code on the walker is modified to respond to the directional buttons and keys 1&2 to rotate clockwise / anit-clockwise. There is a great example project using all these pieces https://learn.adafruit.com/bluefruit-feather-robot/overview.

  • Adafruit Feather 32u4 Bluefruit LE
  • Adafruit DC Motor + Stepper FeatherWing Add-on For All Feather Boards
  • Lithium Ion Polymer Battery - 3.7v

Motors

  • 9V 30RPM Motors
  • powered by 5V USB battery pack
  • voltage boosted to 9V (motor rating) using Pololu 9V Step-Up Voltage Regulator U3V50F9

Other Hardware

  • M4 bolts, nylon washers and nyloc nuts
  • M10 plastic washers (spacers on the crankshaft)
  • 4 mm brass tube - top leg pivot hinges
  • 1/4" square brass tube - crankshaft end supports
It fits air bike pump Ø24.5mm, I remodelled this mount http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1907457 to fit my bigger pump.

title: S-Mount (M12) lens mount for Logitech C920

description.text: S-Mount (M12) lens mount for Logitech C920. Just follow disassembly instructions online to disassemble the webcam, remove the original autofocus lens (remember to desolder the AF power pads, labeled "+" and "-" on the PCB). Attach the printed lens mount to the board with 2 M2x0.8 screws. The holes can be tapped by force-screwing standard machine screws in (my way), or can be tapped if you anticipate having to remove it a few times (the right way). The top is designed for a M12 locking ring like this one - http://www.m12lenses.com/M12x0-5-Lock-Ring-Plastic-p/pt-lr001p.htm (just glue it in or something).

title: LED Support for Stage-Inspired LED Spotlight

description.text:
This addon is for the Stage-Inspired LED Spotlight by Depronized.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2051738

I made this addon to secure the LED curcuitry in place and have it be locked in after the whole Spotlight has been glued together. Also wanted to be able to use short M3 screws, so there are spots you can put the nuts in place before assembly. Recommend using a glue to secure them during assembly.

Check out the LED filter for the Stage-inspired LED Light: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2371483
Enjoy!

Please also check out my Lack Enclosure - Complete Setup
As well as my other Things I've created - Bolerro

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

NA

Step 1

Secure M3 nuts in place by using an M3 screw to seat the nuts and then use glue to secure the nuts. When glueing, remove the screw first so it doesn't get glued in place.

Step 2

Using the reference LED's in the original Spotlight instructions (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2051738). Insert the PCB in the spacer in the orientation that the wires will go along the body of the spacer.

Step 3

Slide the spacer into the spot_back and line up the screw holes. Using an M3x16, attach the spot_holder to the spot_back on each side.

Step 4

Line up the locking collar to the space with the top layer facing the spacer. This should be a tight fit, but the pillars on the spacer will fit into the locking collar.

Step 5

Using whatever type of glue you desire, attach the spot_front or spot_front_short to the assembled spot_back piece. I used Gorilla Super Glue, so I had to use clamps on it until it dried. You should have to squeeze the pieces together with a small amount of pressure. This pressure keeps the locking collar in place and the whole assembly from moving.

Spacer v2 Update

Moved the M3 nut indentations to the outside wall. No more glue to hold the nut in place. The stage light housing will hold the nuts in place now.

description.text:
I've printed a few 5DF spool hubs and so far between strength and speed of printing, the Small spool support (5 Dollar Filament) has my heart, but I'm using smooth 5/16" rod so a standard 608 bearing is super nice to have, it holds things square (enough) and obviously rolls well. Soo I simply updated mrice's design and added a 22.05mmx7mm hub and took out a bit more plastic, because let's face it, it doesn't need to support that much weight, and it allows you to add a nut/bolt weight to stop it from unspooling itself when left unattended :D

Use cheap 'stiff' or grease packed bearings for best results, these little 5DF spools have some spring to them!

Printer:

Anet A2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

40% Cubic 3D

Notes:

Nothing much to add, sliced in Cura, used the amethyst in 1.75 (and it's very transparent, more so than the photos give credit even better at 0.1 res!)

Imported the stl from mrice's thing into tinkercad and made my changes!

Feel free to pick up where I left off and make it your own!

comments.text:
After using this for a few weeks, I've learned they unspool mabye too easy, however! The hexagon shaped holes fit pretty much any size bolt and nut to add some weight to just one side to stop it from unrolling itself! Also being so close to the hub, it really doesn't effect the load on your extruder at all!
I will say again however, cheap, grease filled bearings are a better choice than nice fidget spinner ones!

author: sunnugget

title: NesPI Controller back with optional switch

description.text:
Added a switch-hole on the bottom (very small) to allow for a small switch.

I was using a USB controller for my build, and so I had to solder the leads directly to the USB pads on the Pi Zero. I wanted to still be able to use the USB if I needed it though, so I added a very tiny (3mm I think) switch, to switch between the controller interface, or whatever I connect to the USB.

I know my print in the picture is bad, I was calibrating a new printer, and used it as a test to see if it would fit. The original creator thought it would only fit the original NES controllers, but it does, in fact, fit the new USB ones as well.

NOTE:
If using the cheap USB controllers from China, the D-pad sucks... The last pictures are step-by-step how to fix it. I bought sticky-back craft foam from Michael's, and cut tiny squares. Then I used a razorblade to cut them down to about 1-2mm tall. I stuck them in the "angles" on the D-pad. This fixes the problem, and the controller works like a dream.

I have also included photos of how I wired the controller.

title: Spinner Bearing to Nut Adapter Ring

description.text:
This just adapts a nut to replace expensive 22mm 608 bearings and can add a little extra color to your toy.

The nut I used measures .678in outside. I just had them laying around and they're nothing special. Enjoy. Feel free to convert to metric or remix however you'd like. A credit would be nice if you remix but I didn't exactly invent an anti-matter engine here.
Edit - I took some measurements of the nuts with my calipers, The outside of the nuts I used: 17.17mm/ 87/128in/.678in

I didn't know that there was another one of these already on thingiverse, but this is fully my work. I've included the Fusion 360 file for your convenience and possible modification.

Mine spun for about 2min 28 sec to a dead stop (-2 sec to hit the stopwatch and spin it.)

If you print these, please consider taking a picture and/or writing something. We as Makers can't improve if we don't have feedback. Thanks :D

title: Stack Jack Mini - Modular GPU Support (revised)

description.text:
Stack Jack Mini is designed specifically for computers with a single graphics card 200 mm or larger that sags at the unsupported end. This model uses a custom thread design that provides 1 mm vibration resistant adjustments every one third turn. The movable adjustment parts fit together in such a way that when under pressure they will not move freely.

The modular design, (parts a, b, and c), has a range of 5.5" - 8.5" and can be increased using the 2" (50mm) extension.

The compact design, (parts a and cb), has a range of 4.5" - 7.25".

WARNING: The small diameter of this design can make printing very difficult.

File information:
Stack_Jack_Mini.stl - this file is for visual reference only
S-J_M_a.stl - inner portion of adjustment parts
S-J_M_c.stl - outside portion of adjustment parts
S-J_M_b.stl - base for Stack Jack Mini, (modular version)
S-J_M_e.stl - 50 mm extension
S-J_M_cb.stl - combination base and adjustment portion

Printer:

Monoprice Select Mini

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Infill:

No / included in design

Notes:

Due to the extreme size of these parts adhesion issues may occur. Using a large raft is recommended.

First time assembly

Inserting part 'a' into parts 'c' or 'cb' for the first time will clear any excess material left from printing. It is recommended to screw the parts together partially and take them apart and knock any loose particles out and repeat.

title: Matsushiro BMW M1 tail light lens and bracket with dividers 1/11

description.text:
If you own or know this RC car, you'll know that all the clear plastic parts are molded in the same orange plastic.

Besides the headlamps which I also made clear lenses for, I just finished the rear lenses and I made a bracket thatll hold a 3mm and a 5mm LED and also divide the inside of the lens so that light from the LEDs are confined to illuminate only the part of the lens theyre supposed to.

I used Tamiya translucent paint (26 and 27) for painting the outside of the lens and therefore i made painting guides on the lenses of .5x.5mm to prevent the paint from flowing accross the whole surface.

Demo video here: https://youtu.be/tQtDzr_Q1GY

Printer:

Creality CR-10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0,25mm for T-glase and 0,2 for PLA

Infill:

100% on both T-Glase and PLA

Notes:

I used the standard .4mm nozzle for both filaments and as the paint guides are .5mm wide and deep, you shouldn't have the extrusion width set too high despite it being a good choice for T-Glase, as the paint guides simply wont be printed; besides you'll also want the lines to be visible in order to break the light, a 100% clear lens wouldnt look too good when lit up imo.

The lenses were printed from the bottom up (like theyre installed on the car) to achieve a consistent print around the curve where the indicator goes and to make the lines of filament as long as possible.

For the bracket, I used plain white PLA.

Design process

As with the other things I made, I used Autodesk Inventor (Im trying to learn this program and these lenses with no 90 degree angles in the design was a great challenge) to create the parts which I measured out using vernier calipers.

Note that the original lenses arent true scale, as far as I can tell, their height/width ratio is off as theyre too wide.

So to divide the lenses for coloring, I did a rough measure on a picture of a rl lens and noted that the rev light was approx 30% and the indicator 20% of the total width, so I went with those figures and scaled the different areas of the lens from that.

title: Anet A8 E3D Titan Aero Mount & Fan Duct

description.text:
Update 1/4/18: New version available! (Anet A8 Titan Aero Mount v2 w/ inductive sensor mount)

I upgraded my Anet A8 extruder to the E3D Titan Aero extruder/heatsink/hot-end combo. This design puts everything along the X axis on a horizontal path. I've attached a picture of my setup so you can see what the finished part will look like.

At this thickness, the parts are highly rigid (even in the PETG that I printed them with) and should be able to stand up to the same level of abuse as the original steel carriage.

In order to keep from having to print supports, the carriage prints in 2 pieces. Because of this, there will be additional thickness over the factory carriage.

You will need 8 M4x10mm screws - the original M4x8mm screws are not long enough to go through both parts and into the linear bearings securely.

I've also included the STL file for a new fan duct, since the fan has moved and typical A8 fan ducts will no longer be that useful. The biggest reason I moved the fan is because the big extruder gear changes the depth of the carriage quite significantly. Note: with this fan duct, you will likely have to adjust extruder temp (mine's about 3 degrees different) while it's on because it does blow over the nozzle a bit

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.4mm / 0.25mm layer height

Infill:

40%

Notes:

Note: I printed with PETG, use whatever layer height you typically use for structural parts.

Use at least 4-6 shells to improve part strength as well as multiple solid top/bottom layers.

Part fan being used will improve strength as well.

Infill percentage is up to you, I printed at 100% but anything above 20% should be just fine.

title: FPV Camera Servo Mount (TVL1000 camera for gimbal)

description.text:
This is a simple design, made out of my TVL1000 adapter for HS1177 camera mounts. It attaches to either a metal or plastic geared 9g servo and allows for a super simple pan setup for your FPV camera.

Two versions are included for the plastic and metal sized heads commonly found on cheap 9g servos. I used a coating of acetone on the ABS I used to soften the plastic to make a very solid grip to the splines on the output shaft.

The hole for the servo arm retaining screw will need to be drilled to the appropriate size. and the design allows for a screwdriver to tighten the screw before you fit the Eachine TVL1000 camera.

We are using this print in the new HobbyKing T-28 Trojan model canopy. Perfect size..

It is NOT a good idea to use a filament guide that is perched on the top cross-beam of the printer, because the whole extruder carriage will be pulled up (every so slightly, but enough to be noticeable on your prints) when the extruder tugs on the filament.

Instead, use a spool on the side (preferable with a 'frictionless' balanced bearing spool-holder), and use this filament guide which i. ensures that the filament enters the extruder straight, and i. reduces the force of unspooling the filament on the extruder's Hobb wheel.

Install by simply gluing it to the steel U-frame of the extruder carriage.

title: Launchpad for FPV Racing, workbench and Model stands

description.text:
Ich glaube hier muss mal ein bisschen Innovation rein, dieses Launchpad, workbench und ständer für die Quads, ist recht praktisch. Es pass so ziemlich jeder 3“ bis 6“ Quad drauf, ausser die überlangen wie Vendetta.
LiPos unten/oben egal es bleibt nichts hängen, das Ding einfach aufklappen, mit den Snappern fixieren, Winkel wählen und losfliegen. Die Start-Winkel können mit 0°, 15°, 20°, 25°, 30°, 35° gewählt werden.
Das Ding hat sich bis jetzt echt gut bewährt, bei Rennen, nassem Untergrund, im Gras, mal abwarten was Ihr dazu meint.

Zusammengeklappt misst das Lauchpad 140mm x 170mm x 30mm, das bedeutet auch, dass Ihr eine Druckfläche von 140mm x 170mm haben solltet. Je dichter gefüllt desto schwerer das Launchpad und Gewicht ist gut…

Hab neu die Seitenteile aufgeteilt, falls Probleme beim Druck als Ganzes. Das muss halt jetzt geklebt werden.

Hier kann man auch eins bestellen FPVracing.ch

Was Ihr alles noch dazu braucht:

Filamente:

Ich denke mal es ist fast egal mit was Ihr druckt, die ersten hab ich mit PLA gemacht und die neusten mit FormFutura FlexiFil™ - Flexible TPC, praktisch unzerstörbar.

Montage:

Alles Edelstahl Zylinderkopfschrauben und Sicherungsmuttern

  • 4 x M4x12mm für Bodenplatte und Seitenteile
  • 2 x M3x30mm für die Snapper in der Bodenplatte
  • 2 x M3x18mm für die Arme an den Seitenteilen
  • 2 x M3x12mm für die Streben an den Armen
  • 4 x M4 Sicherungsmuttern
  • 6 x M3 Sicherungsmuttern

title: Vintage Pepperidge Farm Jabba the Hutt Cookie Mold/Cutter

description.text:
This cookie mold/cutter was made specifically to try and recreate the Jabba the Hutt cookie that came in the Star Wars cookies that Pepperidge Farm made in 1983 (see the accompanying YouTube video: https://www.youtube.com/edit?o=U&video_id=CnN2brAo79Y). It's not the easiest cutter to use for that reason, so if you're just looking for a Jabba cookie cutter I will be uploading something more appropriate soon. This is a two-part mold, with the inside part making the design and the outside part doing the cutting (leaving a bit of a border around the design).

If you do want to try using it, make sure you're using a dough that is suitable (not a ready-made dough). I recommend chilling it in the refrigerator for a few minutes after rolling it out, and also be sure to dust the dough and the cutter with flour or powdered sugar. You can make the cutter bigger if you want, but I found that making it much smaller made it hard to see the detail.

description.text:
Power casing for HICTOP Prusa I3.

HICTOP printers supplied to date have inadequate insulation at the power supply. The mains voltage can be accessed inadvertently by hand. Children should not be allowed access to these printers. This power cover makes your HICTOP safer by adding a layer of insulation and add a mains power switch.

This fits the models shipped in Spring 2017 with 24 volt power supply. It is mounted using two M4 bolts. The electrical inlet is supplied by CPC Farnell in the UK part number CN14758. You will also need to order a 5X20 quick blow fuse of appropriate rating and voltage (I use 5 amps/240v). The wiring requires 3 spade connectors and a short length of mains cable.

http://cpc.farnell.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/ProductDisplay?catalogId=15002&langId=69&urlRequestType=Base&partNumber=CN14758&storeId=10180

I have included the Fusion 360 source file.

DO NOT MAKE THIS ITEM IN AN ELECTRICALLY CONDUCTIVE MATERIAL.

title: Nut Fastener M3 - M8 (2 Finger Fastener)

description.text:
With these Nut Fasteners you can fasten hex-nuts by hand using two or three fingers. I made 5 dimensions (M3, M4, M5, M6, M8). The printing is very easy. No need for supports, Rafts or similar (see printing section).
You can fasten normal hex-nuts (e.g. DIN 980) as well as locking nuts (e.g. Din 985). The hollow space that holds the hex-nut has an additional torous hollow on the top, so that locking nuts fit smoothly in.
On the pictures you can see the M3, M4, M5 and M6 versions (I didn't print the M8 yet).
Feedback is highly apreciated. Have fun!

UPDATE 16.04.2017
Please remark: The nut hollows are designed very tight, so that nuts can be fastened as strong as possible without "slipping" through. Depending on your slicer/printer's printing accuracy, I recommend to print the M3 version first and to try if a M3 nut fits in. If needed scale the stl file in your slicer accordingly.

description.text:
DEPRECATED. See:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2429919

21/04/2017 - I have uploaded a reworked version fixing some issues. It should work, but I can not test it, as I no longer have a working hybrid head. If you try this design and it works. Thanks.

Aelos is a case for the FABtotum hybrid head PCB.

You must own such a hybrid head (or maybe alternatively a V2 Milling head, you will have to check as I do not own one). It is possible that you can buy one second hand, as many people don't mill and print quality is not hybrid heads strongest point. Post in the forum.

If you remove the extruder from the hybrid head:
https://github.com/Opentotum/Opentotum/wiki/hybrid-head-v1-extruder-removal

now you have some space for dust extraction.

This head is designed to accommodate a 24 mm diameter pipe. My best match is a washing machine dirty water pipe like this one:

http://www.hornbach.de/shop/Ablaufschlauch-100-cm/7309601/artikel.html

Both end connectors are not the same size. Only one fits in "Aeolos".

For my very reduced trials so far, the other end fits a Dyson v6 absolute (without any v6 accessory mounted). I plan to design a different solution.

Why is this a thing in progress?

Well my flex cable has degraded further and now I do not have 24 V in the carriage anymore. I simply cannot mill and I cannot test it with the milling motor on

Printer:

FABtotum with

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

I printed mine in ABS in 0.3 mm layers.

You need supports. If you can use a double extruder with a soluble support this is a good chance to use it. Cleaning this part out of support takes around 3 hours and a lot of patience. Use an easy to remove support!!!

This design is extremely sensible to warping. If it warps 1 mm in the edges you won't be able to fit the PCB without reworking the PCB area. For this reason, it may make a lot of sense to print it in PLA (I have run out of PLA and I am testing "Zeus" with ABS, so I had non-technical reasons to do it in ABS).

Cleaning support

If you can use a double extruder with a soluble support this is a good chance to use it. Cleaning this part out of support takes around 3 hours and a lot of patience. This is because I wanted just one part enclosing the duct and maximize the section for the airflow.

FreeCAD v0.17

Fully designed with FreeCAD v0.17. Full source attached. Take a recent version as it uses B-splines in the Sketcher.

description.text:
Roughly 250 class (255mm) quadcopter model with multiple options to build. Arms have mounting points for 2204-II, 16 and 19mm. FC mount is 30.5mm.

Possible combos;

  • GoPro Session box camera-quad, with internal battery compartment.
  • 3 different heights for sleek non-FPV (LOS) racer

Multiple parts, not all needed to build. Sample version with pictures are built from:

  • arm.stl (4 pc)
  • esc_cover.stl (4 pc)
  • baseplate.stl
  • subframe_with_baseplate_support.stl
  • top_cover.stl

Sample quad is equiped with:

  • Seriously Pro Racing F3 controller (30.5mm mount holes)
  • EMax 2204-II 2300kv motors
  • 15A ESC
  • 5x4.5 bullnose propellers
  • 800mAh/3S (45C) LiPo, gives roughly 4-5 minutes flight time

Sample quad printing settings;

  • Dremel Idea Builder PLA
  • 0.4 nozzle
  • 0.25mm layers
  • 33% infill (honeycomb)

To build GoPro Session video quad:

  • esc_cover.stl (4 pc)
  • baseplate.stl
  • subframe_with_baseplate_support.stl
  • box_frame_for_gopro_session.stl
  • top_cover_thin.stl

comments.text: Hi, could you add any information how to print it? infill %? I can see that main part should be printed with supports? I want to add this upgrade to my A6
comments.author: Cosik

comments.text: I recommend printing it in ABS or PET-G. I used 0,2mm resolution with a 0.4mm nozzle. 20% infill with a 3 or 4 layer wall count should make it more than strong enough :-). You do not have to let your slicer program generate support material. Instead I put a cylinder in the model on the place where the Hot End will sit. This way it takes less Filament and you don't have to clean the Model afterwards :-).

description.text:
This is an enclosure for a sonoff IoT switch. The enclosure provides a means of protecting the device and enhances cable strain relief if used in conjunction with cable ties and the holes at the rear of the enclosure. The lid is vented, and the holes allow LED status to be viewed, it's got a lip, and can be secured with countersunk screws (and/or cable ties). The enclosure is large enough to house the device and eg an external by-pass earth lead.

The suitability of this enclosure is fine for my application, but you may need a different/better one for your application. Electricity is dangerous, seek professional advice if unsure about anything.

The photographs are of a previous version of this enclosure. I have rounded both the lid and the box corners, and the vent holes in the lid are smaller and more numerous than than those in the photograph.

description.text: Don't want to use film canisters, pill bottles or KCups to hold your miniatures or other items for printing? No problem!

The well build Metz 45ct series flashes could use a nice compact mount to support umbrella's. Well, here it is. And yes, I like intersecting cylinders a lot... Versions 1.3 moutpoint for camera tripod
2.1 includes tilt clamp for lamp stand
2.5 fixed rendering problems, moved tripod fixing screw to a better location.
2.6 added support material for fixing screw
2.7 changed to M6 stepbolt for tilting.

Print, if you printed the 1.x version, tap 1/4" thread and mount it on a camera tripod. the 2.x version needs a M6 bolt and nut. Slide your flash (strobe) on the thing and stick the ubrella in the 8mm hole. Fix with a additional screw. the wedged side mount on the spot where the original metal camera-plate was situated. For balance, slide the flash with the business end towards the mounting lip so the tripod head is nearest to the flash bulb.
Protip: print metz_clip_test.scad to test the tolerance in the wedge. adjust spacing variables in the grip() module. The stl files are here for imaging purposes only.
Reworked to include tilt clamp to mount it on a standard small spigot-style lamp stands like the Manfrotto 004. Support material added for this one as some parts are floating (tripod mount screw body)

I extracted the mesh from the Skyrim game engine, but it was a really low detail model (image #2), so I recreated the model using ZBrush in very high detail. You should probably only print this if you have a good resolution printer for best results (I don't use the makerbot printer, I use the Form1 SLA printer, which prints this perfectly). The model is hollow to save on material.  
If you do end up printing this on your FDM printer, let me know how it turns out!  
You might even need a decent computer to open the model, it's 1.8 million polys, so keep that in mind when working with this.  
I spent a lot of time modeling this, but it still belongs to Bethesda, so don't go around selling this.
There are two different models, one with a base and one without a base.

TronXY X3 Table Fitting.
Table must be regulate approximately every ten hours of work. I offer this solution for easy regulation.
Addition parts:

  1. 6 nut M5 S8.
  2. 6 screws M5x20.
    Assembly:
  3. Install rollers to swings using regular spacers.
  4. Install swings to fitting.
    Installation:
  5. Install conductor at existing holes in the table.
  6. Drill two holes dia 5 through conductor.
  7. Remove conductor.
  8. Install fitting.

Note: "TronXY_X3_Table_FTG_RHS" using for replace regular spacers.

As you can read in my blog, the business case for my Orca was won when I told my wife I would design replacable high heel ends.
So I did
www.3daybreaker.blogspot.com

Take of the worn heel-surface with some pliers
Measure if the replacement part would fit your shoe :-)
(If not, the source is there to change)
Print the high heel stop in a shoe-matching color, put a parker through it from the wide side, sink it untill it stops, put some glu on the other side and screw it in the high heel.
Replace them when the wear reaches the screw head.

description.text:
23/04/2017 UPDATE

This is the integrated version only now, the enclosure version is here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2265113

Followed MK CUB3D (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2188337) design deeper, used most of his parts but the Z-TOPS, I uploaded new STL versions of this parts and SketchUp files.

Will not be using the MK2-X parts by now.

Still, need to work on electronics relocation and how to complete close the bottom.

UPDATE 4/19/2017

  • Added 2 versions, one enclosure only, and the second step started the haribo modification.
  • If you have sketchup pro, you can click on the door to open and on the bed for Y movement, it moves the full range to test positions (will add x and Z movement in the future, just for fun)
  • moved the power source to the right on the enclosure version
  • still not sure about hight I think I will make it taller so the enclosure will end at 500500600

ORIGINAL

I'm designing a 3030 based enclosure for the Original Prusa MK2, but want to transform it to a "Prusa i3 MK2-X" remix http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1692666 . So testing that everything fits inside.

My main focus now is the enclosure and electronics relocation. First building step will be fitting the Original Prusa MK2 without frame changes.

The enclosure has a transparent lid.

I Included a SketchUp file. The lid is an interactive component, you can "click" it to open or close.

description.text:
I was looking for a way to attach my Xiaomi YI (with the "standard" GoPro-style clip) to my backpack. — This is what I came up with.

No other parts (velcro, screws, etc.) are needed and the whole construction is - at least in my opinion - unobstrusive enough to stay on the backpack.

I remixed Ivanlings flat clip into a mounting plate that goes under the webbing that many backpacks have on top of their shoulder straps. (Thanks for the inspiration, McAlex!)

You can adjust the length, width and height of the plate, as well as the width and depth of the channel for the strap to make it fit onto your own backpack. :)

Example recorded using this clip: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sRpvvKygfVM

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.10mm

Infill:

70%

Notes:

The tabs that actually lock the camera clip in place need to be printed with supports. The "leftovers" from these supports make for quite a tight fit at the beginning. This should (in my case it did) get better after inserting and removing the camera clip a couple of times.

It's also a good idea to print with a relatively high infill. I used 70%.

I used black PLA from Esun.

  • Bed: 60°C
  • Hotend: 210°C

title: Nylord Mini Quad 212 FPV

description.text:
This is my latest mini quad - "The Nylord" It is intended to be printed in nylon. It is a 212 size mini quad and prints very well in 910 Nylon and is very strong. Comes with Camera Mount and is set up for 2200 series motors. You'll need some standoffs, I recommend Aluminum they can be found on Banggood and Ebay. Happy Printing and flying! If you're into the hobby, it will all make sense, if not you'll figure things out ;)

Printing on Glass with hairspray. 910 Nylon, first layer 245, bed 80... All other layers 235 bed 20. Do not use cooling fan for parts, print around 35mm per second. Nice, slow and steady.

Also added a thicker body version that is 7.5mm in thickness as well as a thicker top plate for anyone who wants a bit more ridged frame.

title: HyperCube 3D Printer M4 Variant
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
HyperCube 3D Printer M4 Variant

This is a derivation of Tech2C's excellent HyperCube 3D printer. Most noticable differences to original parts are M4 holes for mounting plastic parts to I-type extrusions.

See links below for other things related to my customized HyperCube 3D printer build.

Only modified parts are contained here. For the full list of parts, refer to the original build instructions.

Modifications

M4 holes

All parts that mount to 20x20 extrusions are modified to use M4 screws instead of the default M5. Therefore it's possible to use Type I extrusions which have a 5mm slot and can take M4 nuts max.

Round holes

The rectangular slots that allow putting nuts through a part are replaced with round (elongated) holes. There's no need to have large slots if you use t-slot sliding nuts that can be inserted to the slot anywhere.

Slot guide for Z endstop adjust

The Z endstop adjust now has a small slot guide to prevent twisting.

See also

Other things related to my customized HyperCube 3D printer build:

  • 2020 Corner Bracket
  • HyperCube Mini IR Probe Mount

Changelog

  • 2017-05-22: Fixed z endstop slot guide orientation
  • 2017-04-30: Added Dual_bushing_holder and simple 2020 corner brackets

(Disclaimer) PLEASE NOTE: These Robox branded sunglasses do not protect your eyes from the sun at all since they don't include lenses.

The sides clip into place, and are a friction fit. The fit is quite tight, we used a hard flat tool to push them into place (metal ruler). If it's too tight, just trim some material off the hinge with a knife - but be careful!

description.text:
So the springs here, we all love water rockets, and i needed a fin assembly for my large rocket. nothing here had 4 fin brackets that i could find, so i designed this for you all.
fits a 98mm Outer diameter bottle, scale up or down as you wish, it can be tricky to get the perfect fit! :-)
Please use nylon bolts or screws when assembling your fin bracket, bottles under pressure mixed with metal is not a good nor safe combo!!

The holes are made about 1mm in diameter for the screws, feel free to drill them to your exact specifications ;-)

Did i mention that if you print two of theese 4 part assemblys, you will have a very good fin system for even a large rocket.
They are designed with splines to be self aligning.

Have FUN!

description.text:
A 3-D rendering of a trefoil knot, by taking a parametric path representation and "thickening" to form a solid (but not so much that the knot self-intersects). The design starts in Sage, export to X3D (resulting file included), edit X3D in Blender (to remove some artifacts Sage leaves behind, like a cube of lines around the figure) and export to STL, import STL into Cura, scale (because graph units in Sage become millimeters in Cura) and situate figure on print platform, then export STL again to form the STL thing file here.

Here is the Sage code to generate the figure:

t = var('t')
parametric_plot3d([sin(t)+2*sin(2*t), cos(t)-2*cos(2*t), -1*sin(3*t)],(t,0,2*pi), thickness=50, aspect_ratio=1)

Since Sage is Python-based, be sure to check line breaks. Note that the surface is defined parametrically and plotted using the parametric_plot3d() method, with a large enough "thickness" setting to make the knot pretty substantial.

Obligatory nod to artist M.C. Escher:
http://www.mcescher.com/Gallery/recogn-bmp/LW444.jpg

So, I had this Sol Republic Tracks Air HD, that come with their bluetooth "V8 Engines".
After 2 years using it, my headband broke and the ear cushions started to crack the foam. I didn't want to buy a new one and pay like U$20, so I decided to make my own thing.

I made a 3d model for the V8 engines, both sides, since they are different, I made custom earcups for each side and remixed some pieces from keganholtzhausen's design.

If you are going to buy new cushions for this, the size should be 100x90mm.

This model I made, allow you to use the earcups with the original headband from Sol Republic. Since this headphone are Bluetooth, the original headband have some copper wires from one side to the other.

I will study a possibility to make ir usable wireless with the printed arms.

title: Kossel 3D printer (Anycubic linear delta) bed leveling

description.text:
This is my first trial to correct the problem of not having automatic leveling. I tried to make it tough, but still not enough for a very precise leveling. It works, but I was dreaming I would be able to keep the calibration even after removing the bed because I had the extra nuts (the thin ones) to lock it...
Another side effect is the shrunk printing area. With the new adaptors I had to setup Cura with 150mm instead of the original 180mm (but I really don't think this printer would be capable of printing something close to 180mm of diameter).

Hint: if your printer is not very precise, scale up the nuts inside Cura (or Slic3r) before generating the g-code. I suggest scaling only X and Y dimensions by 101% (or scale factor 1.01).

How to assemble it
The Nut_counter is the first nut (from bottom to top). If you look at the first photograph, you may see it. It is supposed to lock the big, tough, nut.

Step-by-step:
1) Attach the Base to your printer (you should center it in relation to each triangle vertice).
2) Add the Nut_counter and put it all the way down to free the way.
3) Add the Nut.
4) Add your printer bed.
5) Add the Nut_small_new.
6) Level the bed using the Nut and the Nut_small_new.
7) Use the Nut_counter to lock the Nut.
8) Print the AnycubicTestRing140 to verify if it's working. I also paused the printer to correct the bed level during the very first layers.

Be careful, depending on your setup for brim/skirt, your printer may hit the bed levelers when printing the AnycubicTestRing140 test file. I've changed my Machine settings to a bed with diameter of 150mm to avoid surprises.

This bed leveler is not a very good solution because it's quite hard to get the leveling right and if you remove the bed plate you will need to redo it. In the future, I will design something better that allows me to attach an extra removable bed plate or, even better, remove the one I have without ruining the leveling.

Here I'm explaining how I did it:
http://ricardodeazambuja.com/3d_printing/2017/04/16/bed_levelling_blu-tack/

If you liked this thing, don't forget to visit my personal website: ricardodeazambuja.com

DISCLAIMER: use it at your own risk ;)

description.text:

author: millsjw

description.text:
Made a new system of spinner.
see video https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XfVvqdrHeaE

Needs bearings 696 (6x15x5mm) - 4pcs
M3x14mm bolt - 4 pcs
self-locking nut M3 - 4 pcs
balls 22mm -3pcs
(or you can take 7/8" (22.225mm) balls and print outer ring +08mm)

need to be printed:
frame A, frame B, roller - 3pcs, cap A, cap B, and outer ring.

I printed outer ring +06mm - with tolerance 0.6mm,
maybe you will need +0.4mm or +0.8mm - dont know...
with balls 7/8" print +0.8mm.
AND NEED A LOT OF GOOD SANDING for outer ring,
so that the inner surface is perfectly smooth.

In openscad you can try use other models of bearings and balls, but with 608 nothing will work out - too big. Openscad file supports animation.
So that the bearings 696 are correctly drawn, you need to replace the standard file from the library MCAD with the bearing.scad

Аналог для подшипников 696 - это 1000096.

title: Hex Hinge for Extruder Heatsink (Anet A8)

description.text:
This is my version of
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2057295
from
http://www.thingiverse.com/Kelle8

This is a great mod if your sick of having to take your hole assembly apart to fix a jam, remove your hot end, or just load your filament.

I changed it up a it with hex holes to go with my motif, and I moved the fan closer to the extrusion body, so this might not work with the heat sink anymore.

I just screw the fan in, and leave the heat sink off. If the heat sink isn't secure to the assembly, it will just be in the way of cooling, so I just have the fan blowing on the assembly and the motor. Many people have had success just removing the fan, so this should work fine.

An added benefit is that the fan can sit more then 90 degrees from the assembly so Its blowing air up slightly, and therefore cooling the heating block less.

When I saw the picture with the dancing function stickmen for the first time, I instantly knew that those cute looking figures have to be transformed into a 3D printable version too - and here they are! 15 dancing stickmen, each of them showing a function with it´s arms.

There are two possibilities of using them, that came to my mind:

  • The first one is quite simple. Just print them and put some pretty decorative mathematical beauty onto your shelf!
  • The second method for using these figures is meant to be a possibility for teachers when the students start getting in touch with functions. The full figures can be used to show how all the functions look like, the cut versions may be used as a game to practice the funcion skills. The students get the top parts as well as the bottom parts and have to put them together in the correct way.
    This can also be played as a simple competition. Each student has to put the stickmen together, and the fastest, who got all of them right, is the winner!
    Maybe you also want to print them a trophy for their success - here's one you may like! www.thingiverse.com/thing:1609476

So, no matter what you want to use these dancing function stickmen for, have fun with them and please let me know if you have wishes for any other functions, I´m always ready to design them for you!

A simple, printable pan/tilt assembly. It needs two servo motors (I've used HITEC HS-422, so the servo bracket fits that). Also, an attachment is provided to be able to couple the 'contraption' to a tripod with an RC2 (Manfrotto) plate. See the photo how to put it together. If anybody needs to know, that is a Devantech TPA81 thermal sensor array on the top... If you are really interested, you can check the pan/tilt head out at: http://www.amzsaki.com/?page_id=343

I've had success printing it with a 25% infill and 3 shell layers in ABS plastic on a Thing-o-matic. It is a compromise between strength and my patience to wait for it to print.
For the mounting holes you have to figure out where to drill based on your servos and availability of screws. I've used #6 machine screws to form the hinge between the two brackets forming the tilt mechanism and the screws that came with the servos to mount the pan servo to the bottom bracket, the tilt servo to the hinge, to the servo bracket and the tilt servo bracket to the bottom bracket. You need to print: 2x bracket.stl (forms the tilt mechanism)
1x bracketA.stl (cradles the servo for the tilt)
1x tripodattachment (optional, if you need one)

description.text: This is a design I created for my 3 extruder Leapfrog Creatr HS. It borrows from the Prometheus system. Its designed to be used with 1.75mm filament and 4mm PTFE tubing, and pass through style pneumatic connectors.

Notes:

Here is the Gcode I use in Simplify3D to change filament. You'll need to update the retraction speeds and distances to match your setup

; Tool Chage Script Start
G1 X20 Y20 F4000;
G1 E-30 F5000
G1 E-150 F2400;
{IF NEWTOOL=0}T0;
{IF NEWTOOL=1}T1;
{IF NEWTOOL=2}T2;

G1 E180 F2400;

; Tool Chage Script Start

You'll need to thread each end. M10 tap.

Connectors: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01IB81IHG/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

comments.text: Your script is great, however, it assumes that at the start of the print, all extruders are E0.
comments.author: lensfort

comments.text: I upgraded my machine to Duet wifi and control all of this through tfree.g tpre.g and tpost.g. Much simpler. I think I originally had 3 prime cubes (one for each nozzle) and those always printed first? I remember this being a huge pain and most times I would manually edit gcode to avoid starting issues.
comments.author: lensfort

comments.text: How does that board and those files make it any better?
comments.author: MattJohnson3030

comments.text:
The duet lets you make custom macro files for when the when a tool is freed, what happens before a new tool is selected, and what happens after. This allows you to set the starting tool before the print starts. It basically replaces the tool change code in S3D. I dont have the exact script in front of me but psudo code would look something like:
tfree0.g
;move the bed down
;move the head off the bed
tpre0.g
; retract 200mm
tpost0;
;extrude 200mm
;extrude a little more to purge
;resume

I wasn't able to find a knob that i liked so i created on. It as worked well for me so far.

This was designed or the NewMatter Mod-T printer using PLA.

The case may need a brim to prevent lifting at the corners. Inside the design there is commented out option for printing a small brim at the corners.

There are two sets of stand offs. One is for the PCB and the other is for the cover screws. The holes in the stand off may need to be drilled out or tapped depending on what you are wanting or your screw size. Also the cover screws need to be 1 1/4 inch. You can make the standoffs taller and their holes to match for shorter screws.

The LED holes don not line up with their location on the PCB. This is because I put mine on short cables so they could be better located and mounted pointed forward instead of upward. The holes are for 3mm LEDs.
